### Human settlement in Wales
# Brecon

*   [Welsh](/Welsh_language): Aberhonddu

![Brecon location within Powys](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Brecon_in_Powys.svg/200px-Brecon_in_Powys.svg.png)
Brecon

Location within [Powys](/Powys)

A rather quaint settlement, [Brecon](/Brecon) (pronounced as /ˈbrɛkən/, should you care; [3] in [Welsh](/Welsh_language), it’s Aberhonddu, which sounds like [ˌabɛrˈhɔnði], a detail that often escapes the casual observer) was once, in more archaic times, known as Brecknock. This [market town](/Market_town) is nestled in [Powys](/Powys), right in the heart of mid [Wales](/Wales), a region that has seen centuries pass with varying degrees of significance. In 1841, its population was a modest 5,701 individuals, [4] a number that crept up to 7,901 by 2001, [5] and then, with a burst of demographic ambition, reached 8,250 by the 2011 census.

Historically, [Brecon](/Brecon) held the rather grand title of [county town](/County_town) for [Brecknockshire](/Brecknockshire) (or Breconshire, for those less inclined to mouthfuls). This particular distinction, however, diminished somewhat with the rather pragmatic formation of the County of [Powys](/Powys). Despite this bureaucratic reshuffling, [Brecon](/Brecon) stubbornly maintains its status as an important local hub, clinging to its past relevance. It currently ranks as the third-largest town in [Powys](/Powys), trailing only [Newtown](/Newtown,_Powys) and [Ystradgynlais](/Ystradgynlais) – a fact that probably keeps its civic leaders up at night. Geographically, it finds itself just north of the dramatic [Brecon Beacons](/Brecon_Beacons) mountain range, comfortably within the designated boundaries of the [Brecon Beacons National Park](/Brecon_Beacons_National_Park). One might say it’s perfectly positioned for those who enjoy both rugged landscapes and the occasional market day.

