[Nia Roberts](/Nia_Roberts_(actress)), 2015

[Brecon](/Brecon), like any town of its age, has spawned its fair share of individuals who went on to achieve some measure of notoriety, for better or worse.

*   [Sibyl de Neufmarché](/Sibyl_de_Neufmarch%C3%A9) (ca.1100 – after 1143): Countess of [Hereford](/Hereford) and, rather impressively, *[suo jure](/Suo_jure)* Lady of Brecknock. A woman who held power in her own right, a rare feat for her time.
*   [Gerald of Wales](/Gerald_of_Wales) (ca.1146 – ca.1223): A [Cambro-Norman](/Cambro-Norman) priest and historian. Known for his rather colourful accounts of [Wales](/Wales), often with a healthy dose of self-promotion.
*   [William de Braose](/William_de_Braose_(died_1230)) (ca.1197 – 1230): A powerful [Marcher lord](/Marcher_lord). [52] His life was, predictably, filled with feudal intrigue and conflict.
*   [Dafydd Gam](/Dafydd_Gam) (ca.1380 – 1415): An archer who met his end fighting for [Henry V](/Henry_V_of_England) at the rather decisive [Battle of Agincourt](/Battle_of_Agincourt). A testament to loyalty, or perhaps just bad luck.
*   [Edward Stafford, 3rd Duke of Buckingham](/Edward_Stafford,_3rd_Duke_of_Buckingham) (1478–1521): An English nobleman whose life ended somewhat abruptly due to accusations of treason. A common occupational hazard for the aristocracy.
*   [Dafydd Epynt](/Dafydd_Epynt) (15th Century): A poet, whose verses, one hopes, were more enduring than his biography.
*   [Hugh Price](/Hugh_Price_(lawyer)) (ca.1495 – 1574): The esteemed founder of [Jesus College, Oxford](/Jesus_College,_Oxford). Education, it seems, was a more stable legacy than nobility.
*   [Admiral Sir William Wynter](/William_Wynter) (ca.1521 – 1589): A principal officer of the [Council of the Marine](/Council_of_the_Marine), a crucial figure in England's burgeoning naval power.
*   [Henry Vaughan](/Henry_Vaughan) (1621–1695): A physician and author, and a significant figure among the [Metaphysical poets](/Metaphysical_poets). [53] His works are still, rather remarkably, studied today.
*   [John Jeffreys](/John_Jeffreys_(died_1689)) (ca.1623 - 1689): A landowner and politician, and the first master of the [Royal Hospital Kilmainham](/Royal_Hospital_Kilmainham). A man of property and public service.
*   Captain Thomas Phillips [54] (late 17th century): The aforementioned commander of the [Hannibal](/Hannibal_(slave_ship)) slave ship. A dark stain on the town's history, now, thankfully, more openly acknowledged.
*   [Howell Harris](/Howell_Harris) (1714–1773): A Calvinistic Methodist evangelist, who, one imagines, brought a certain fiery passion to his sermons.
*   [Diederich Wessel Linden](/Diederich_Wessel_Linden) (fl. 1745–1768; d. 1769): A specialist in mining and the medicinal properties of mineral waters. A man of practical, if niche, scientific pursuits.
*   [Thomas Coke](/Thomas_Coke_(bishop)) (1747–1814): Not only Mayor of [Brecon](/Brecon) in 1772 but also the first [Methodist](/Methodist) [bishop](/Bishop). [55] A man of both civic and spiritual authority.
*   [Sarah Siddons](/Sarah_Siddons) (1755–1831): A celebrated [tragedienne](/Tragedy) actress. [56] Her dramatic flair still resonates through the annals of theatre history.
*   [David Price](/David_Price_(East_India_Company_officer)) (1762–1835): An orientalist and officer in the [East India Company](/East_India_Company). A man who witnessed the complexities of colonial expansion.
*   [Charles Kemble](/Charles_Kemble) (1775–1854): An actor, and the younger brother of the illustrious [Sarah Siddons](/Sarah_Siddons). [57] Living in the shadow of a famous sibling is a challenge few overcome entirely.
*   [John Evan Thomas](/John_Evan_Thomas) (1810–1873): A Welsh sculptor, whose works, one hopes, still stand somewhere.
*   [Mordecai Jones](/Mordecai_Jones) (1813-1880): A businessman who pioneered the South [Wales](/Wales) coalfield and served as Mayor of [Brecon](/Brecon) in 1854. A man who literally fueled the industrial revolution.
*   [Frances Hoggan](/Frances_Hoggan) (1843–1927): The first British woman to receive a doctorate in medicine. A true pioneer, battling the prejudices of her time.
*   [Ernest Howard Griffiths](/Ernest_Howard_Griffiths) (1851–1932): A physicist and academic, contributing to the ever-expanding realm of scientific understanding.
*   [Gwenllian Morgan](/Gwenllian_Morgan) (1852–1939): The first woman in [Wales](/Wales) to hold the office of Mayor. Another trailblazer, chipping away at the patriarchy.
*   [Llewela Davies](/Llewela_Davies) (1871–1952): A pianist and composer, enriching the cultural tapestry of her era.
*   [Dame Olive Wheeler](/Olive_Wheeler) (1886–1963): An educationist, psychologist, and university lecturer. Shaping minds, one generation at a time.
*   [Captain Richard Mayberry](/Richard_Maybery) (1895–1917): A World War I flying ace, whose brief life was marked by remarkable courage.
*   Lt Col [S. F. Newcombe](/S._F._Newcombe) (1878–1956): An Army Officer and associate of the enigmatic [T. E. Lawrence](/T._E._Lawrence). A man who, one assumes, saw more than his fair share of desert sands.
*   [Tudor Watkins, Baron Watkins](/Tudor_Watkins,_Baron_Watkins) (1903–1983): A politician and MP, navigating the labyrinthine corridors of power.
*   [John Fullard](/John_Fullard) (1907–1973): A tenor singer with the [Covent Garden Opera](/Covent_Garden_Opera). His voice, one can only imagine, soared.
*   [Jet Naessens](/Jet_Naessens) (1915–2010): A Belgian actress and director, born in [Brecon](/Brecon) because her parents had, rather dramatically, fled there during [World War I](/World_War_I). War, it seems, has a way of redistributing talent.
*   [George Melly](/George_Melly) (1926–2007): A [trad jazz](/Trad_jazz) singer, art critic, and writer, who found a retreat in [Brecon](/Brecon) between 1971 and 1999. A man of many talents, finding solace in the Welsh countryside.
*   [Gareth Gwenlan](/Gareth_Gwenlan) (1937–2016): A TV producer, director, and executive, shaping the entertainment landscape for decades.
*   [Roger Glover](/Roger_Glover) (born 1945): The bassist and songwriter with the legendary band [Deep Purple](/Deep_Purple). His riffs, one presumes, still echo through the ages.
*   [Jeb Loy Nichols](/Jeb_Loy_Nichols) (born ca.1965): A musician, adding his voice to the ongoing symphony of human expression.
*   [Nia Roberts](/Nia_Roberts_(actress)) (born 1972): An actress, bringing stories to life on screen and stage.
*   [Gerard Cousins](/Gerard_Cousins) (born 1974): A guitarist, composer, and arranger, weaving intricate musical tapestries.
*   [Natasha Marsh](/Natasha_Marsh) (born 1975): A soprano singer, whose voice, one hopes, is as captivating as her name.
*   [Sian Reese-Williams](/Sian_Reese-Williams) (born 1981): An actress, continuing the tradition of performance.

### Sport

Even in the realm of athletic endeavor, [Brecon](/Brecon) has produced its share of notable figures.

*   [Frederick Bowley](/Frederick_Bowley_(cricketer,_born_1873)) (1873–1943): A first-class cricketer for Worcestershire. A man who knew his way around a wicket.
*   [Walley Barnes](/Walley_Barnes) (1920–1975): A footballer boasting an impressive 299 club caps and 22 for [Wales](/Wales_national_football_team), who later transitioned into broadcasting. A true all-rounder, both on and off the pitch.
*   [Andy Powell](/Andy_Powell_(rugby)) (born 1981): A [Welsh Rugby Union](/Welsh_Rugby_Union) international [number eight](/Number_eight_(rugby_union)). A formidable presence on the rugby field.
*   [Sam Hobbs](/Sam_Hobbs_(rugby_union)) (born 1988): A rugby union player who plied his trade with [Cardiff Blues](/Cardiff_Blues). Another testament to Welsh rugby prowess.
*   [Jessica Allen](/Jessica_Allen) (born 1989): A Welsh racing cyclist. Speed and endurance, embodied.
*   [Emma Plewa](/Emma_Plewa) (born 1990): A footballer with 20 caps for the [Wales women](/Wales_women%27s_national_football_team) national team. A powerful example of female athletic achievement.

## Town twinning

[Brecon](/Brecon) has, rather optimistically, entered into twinning agreements with several international communities. One assumes these relationships are maintained with varying degrees of enthusiasm.

*   [Saline, Michigan](/Saline,_Michigan), United States: An American counterpart, perhaps offering a glimpse into a different cultural landscape.
*   [Blaubeuren](/Blaubeuren), [Baden-Württemberg](/Baden-W%C3%BCrttemberg), Germany: This particular twinning is, it must be noted, with [Brecknockshire](/Brecknockshire) as a larger area of [Powys](/Powys), rather than directly with the town of [Brecon](/Brecon) itself. A subtle, yet important, distinction.
*   [Gouesnou](/Gouesnou), [Brittany](/Brittany), France: A connection to the Celtic cousins across the channel.
*   [Dhampus](/Dhampus), [Kaski District](/Kaski_District), Nepal: A rather geographically ambitious pairing, spanning continents and cultures. One wonders about the commonalities.